\subsection{Trace of a web request: [[mothra http://example.com]]}

%claude:
The traversal of the stack for a single page load is:

\begin{enumerate}

\item Mothra's [[main()]] calls [[url2target]] to canonicalize
[[http://example.com]] into an internal URL object, using
[[mothra/url.c]] (Chapter~\ref{chap:urls}).

\item Mothra opens [[/mnt/web/clone]]. The kernel routes the open
to [[webfs]], which allocates a new [[Client]] structure and returns
a connection number (Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}).

\item Mothra writes the URL to [[/mnt/web/$n$/ctl]]. Webfs parses
it with its full RFC 3986 parser ([[webfs/url.c]]), opens
[[/net/tcp/clone]] (or [[/net/tls/clone]] for HTTPS), and sends
the HTTP request (Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}).

\item Mothra opens [[/mnt/web/$n$/contenttype]] and reads the MIME
type. It uses [[snoop.c]] to dispatch (Chapter~\ref{chap:content-dispatch}).

\item Mothra opens [[/mnt/web/$n$/body]] and reads the bytes through
a pipe to [[uhtml]], which reads them back, sniffs the charset, and
pipes through [[tcs]] if needed (Chapter~\ref{chap:charset}).

\item The UTF-8 bytes reach mothra's [[rdhtml.c]], which tokenizes
the HTML, dispatches on tags, and builds a flat list of [[Item]]s
(Chapter~\ref{chap:html-parsing}).

\item The [[Item]] list is walked by the layout code, which word-wraps
it into text runs and emits libpanel draw calls
(Chapter~\ref{chap:layout} and Chapter~\ref{chap:tag-rendering}).

\item When an [[<img>]] tag is encountered, mothra [[fork]]s a
[[getpix]] subprocess and passes it a handle on the new
[[/mnt/web/$n$/body]]. [[getpix]] decodes the image (possibly piping
through [[resize]] if it is too large) and writes a bitmap that
mothra reads back and blits onto the panel
(Chapter~\ref{chap:images}).

\item The user clicks a link. Libpanel calls the anchor handler,
which extracts the target URL, resolves it against the base, and
goes back to step~2.

\end{enumerate}

\section{Book structure}

%claude:
The book is organized in three parts, preceded by a short preface of
setup chapters and followed by a conclusion and the usual appendices.

%claude:
The {preface} (Chapters \ref{chap:intro}--\ref{chap:mothra-main})
contains this chapter, the core data structures used throughout the
code, and a walkthrough of mothra's [[main()]] and top-level event
loop. Reading [[main()]] early gives you the skeleton on which every
later chapter hangs.

%claude:
{Part~I, Retrieving the Page}, covers everything that happens before
mothra has any bytes to render: URL parsing
(Chapter~\ref{chap:urls}), the warmup HTTP client [[hget]]
(Chapter~\ref{chap:hget}), the [[webfs]] file server
(Chapter~\ref{chap:webfs}), the [[webcookies]] companion
(Chapter~\ref{chap:webcookies}), the retrieval state machine inside
mothra (Chapter~\ref{chap:retrieval}), and the charset pipeline
(Chapter~\ref{chap:charset}). By the end of Part~I, clean UTF-8 bytes
are queued up for the parser.

%claude:
{Part~II, Rendering the Page}, picks up the bytes and turns them
into pixels: HTML parsing (Chapter~\ref{chap:html-parsing}),
MIME-based content dispatch (Chapter~\ref{chap:content-dispatch}),
the layout engine (Chapter~\ref{chap:layout}), the per-tag rendering
rules (Chapter~\ref{chap:tag-rendering}), tables
(Chapter~\ref{chap:tables}), images (Chapter~\ref{chap:images}), and
forms (Chapter~\ref{chap:forms}). By the end of Part~II, the page is
on screen and the user can interact with it.

%claude:
{Part~III, Beyond the Basics}, covers navigation and history
(Chapter~\ref{chap:navigation}), event handling and integration with
the rest of \plan (Chapter~\ref{chap:events}), developer tools
(Chapter~\ref{chap:devtools}), and advanced topics like proxies,
gzip, and FTP (Chapter~\ref{chap:advanced}).

%claude:
The {conclusion} (Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion}) summarizes what has
been covered, highlights the design patterns that recur across the
stack, and compares mothra with [[abaco]] and with modern browsers.
%
The {appendices} cover cross-cutting concerns---debugging, profiling,
error management, and shared utilities.

